The question is vague, but I think I understand enough to answer.

First off, your claim that your &quot;if&quot; statement does nothing at all is false and misleading. If you get an error after pressing the Alpha2 button, that means that the code tried successfully to execute whatever is in the if statement. 

The problem lies in the fact that your Gameobject clone is unassigned. The variable is like an empty shell, or a husk that can contain and point to a gameobject you have inside the game. 

Here&#39;s a very simple piece of code to do the behavior you described:

```c#
[SerializeField] Gameobject clonePrefab; //You have to drag and drop a prefab from Unity here
List&lt;Gameobject&gt; clones=new List&lt;Gameobject&gt;();

void Start(){
    for(i=0,i&lt;10,i++){
        clones.Add(Instantiate(clonePrefab));
    }
}

void Update(){
    if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Alpha2))
        {
            for(i=0,i&lt;clones.Count,i++){
                Destroy(clones[i]);
            }
        }
}
```

